{{unreferenced|date=May 2015}} '''K-5''' (pronounced "kay through five") is an [[United States|American]] term for the [[education]] period from [[kindergarten]] to [[fifth grade]]. It receives equal amounts of criticism and support in the educational industry. While many [[early childhood]] experts deem it too closely aligned with more developmentally inappropriate "watered-down" early elementary teaching methods, [[Administration (government)|administrator]]s and policy-makers see it as a way to integrate kindergarten under the guise of the [[No Child Left Behind Act]] of 2001.
