'''Student.com''' is the largest student accommodation marketplace that helps students find [[residential]] accommodation.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/stevenbertoni/2016/02/10/tech-investors-from-spotify-xiaomi-vy-capital-and-horizon-bet-on-study-abroad-site-student-com/#556dd43932c4 | title=Tech Investors from Spotify, Xiaomi, VY Capital and Horizons Bet On Study Abroad Site Student.com | publisher=[[Forbes]] | date= | accessdate=26 February 2016 | author=Steven Bertoni}}</ref> The company differentiates itself from the other real estate marketplaces by focusing on the untapped student accommodation market, by connecting students to [[professional]] [[landlords]]; identifying and exploiting a niche in the property market.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/02/10/student-com-bags-60m-to-grow-the-reach-of-its-student-digs-marketplace/ | title=Student.com Bags $60M To Grow The Reach Of Its Student Digs Marketplace | publisher=[[Techcrunch]] | accessdate=26 February 2016 | author=Natasha Lomas}}</ref> Student.com was founded by Luke Nolan in 2011 with Shakil Khan and John-Paul Jones joining in 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2016/02/11/university-accommodation-start-up-studentcom-raises-60m.html | title=‘Booking.com for students’ raises $60M | publisher=[[CNBC]] | accessdate=26 February 2016 | author=Arjun Kharpal}}</ref> The company is headquartered in Dubai, with offices in the UK, China, Hong Kong, USA and Australia.
==Company history==
===Inception=== The company was initially founded in 2011 as [https://www.student.com/en-gb/about Overseas Student Living] by Luke Nolan.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://startups.co.uk/accommodation-booking-platform-student-com-clinches-60m/ | title=Accommodation booking platform Student.com clinches $60m | publisher=Startups.co.uk | accessdate=26 February 2016 | author=Henry Williams}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dailynewsx.com/news/technology-news/accommodation-marketplace-student-com-has-raised-60-million-22173.html | title=Accommodation marketplace Student.com has raised $60 million | publisher=Dailynewsx | accessdate=26 February 2016 | author=Daniel McDonald}}</ref> After working in [[China]] for several years, Nolan was regularly called upon by his Chinese friends to help recommend accommodation for students looking to study in the US, UK and Australia. Recognizing that many other individuals, especially students, were facing similar issues, Nolan realized that there was a potential market for an online student accommodation marketplace that could help in connecting students with trusted professional landlords for their accommodation needs.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dealstreetasia.com/stories/30375-30375/ | title=Student.com secures $60m investment in round led by VY Capital | publisher=Dealstreetasia | accessdate=26 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.emea.gr/60-%CE%B5%CE%BA%CE%B1%CF%84.-%CE%B4%CE%BF%CE%BB.-%CE%B3%CE%B9%CE%B1-%CF%84%CE%BF-student.com-%CE%AD%CE%BD%CE%B1-marketplace-%CE%B5%CF%8D%CF%81%CE%B5%CF%83%CE%B7%CF%82-%CF%86%CE%BF%CE%B9%CF%84/473203 | title=60 εκατ. δολ. για το Student.com, ένα marketplace εύρεσης φοιτητικής στέγης | publisher=Emea.gr | accessdate=26 February 2016}}</ref> In 2014, he was joined by other co-founders Shakil Khan, who met Nolan 10-years earlier in Shanghai, and John-Paul Jones.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://thepienews.com/news/student-com-raises-60m-to-build-global-accommodation-reach/ | title=Student.com raises $60m to build global accommodation reach | accessdate=26 February 2016 | author=Natalie Marsh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.itespresso.fr/student-com-leve-60-millions-dollars-net-economie-121331.html | title=Student.com lève 60 millions de dollars : merci la Net-économie | accessdate=26 February 2016 | author=Clément Bohic}}</ref> The company rebranded itself as Student.com in 2015 to focus on expanding globally and hired a team of multilingual booking agents.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/02/10/student-com-raises-60m-and-its-profile-to-help-international-students-find-somewhere-to-live/ | title=Student.com raises $60M (and its profile) to help international students find somewhere to live | publisher=[[VentureBeat]] | accessdate=26 February 2016 | author=Paul Sawers}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://e27.co/xiaomis-vp-spotifys-founders-join-us60m-investment-student-com-20160211/ | title=Xiaomi VP, Spotify Founders join US$60M investment in Student.com | accessdate=26 February 2016 | author=Yon Heong Tung}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://roll.sohu.com/20160215/n437409563.shtml | title=李嘉诚等投资Student.com 涉资4.7亿元 | publisher=[[Sohu.com]] | accessdate=26 February 2016}}</ref>
===Growth and funding=== In 2015, the company saw $110 million in bookings, listed properties in 426 cities in proximity to 1,000 universities.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://techcitynews.com/2016/02/11/online-marketplace-student-com-gets-60m-in-funding/ | title=Property site Student.com gets $60m in funding | accessdate=26 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.androidheadlines.com/2016/02/spotify-founders-xiaomi-vp-invest-in-student-com.html | title=Spotify Founders & Xiaomi VP Invest In Student.com | accessdate=26 February 2016 | author=Kristijan Lucic}}</ref> The company raised combined Series B and C funding of $60 million in 2016 led by VY Capital, [[Horizons Ventures]], Expa, [[Spotify]] founders [[Daniel Ek]] and Martin Lorentzon, and [[Hugo Barra]] of [[Xiaomi]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.redherring.com/finance/student-com-raises-60m-investment-round/ | title=Student.com Raises $60m Investment Round | work=[[Red Herring (magazine)|Red Herring]] | accessdate=26 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.builderonline.com/newsletter/studentcom-bags-60m-to-grow-the-reach-of-its-student-digsmarketplace_c | title=STUDENT.COM SCORES $60M FOR ITS STUDENT DIGS PLAY | accessdate=26 February 2016}}</ref>
==Products and features== The listings on Student.com are displayed on an interactive map subdivided by different neighborhoods.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://edu.sina.com.cn/a/2015-11-18/doc-ifxkwuwy6956823.shtml | title=Student.com亮相中国 留学住哪儿不用愁 | publisher=[[Sina Corp|Sina]] | accessdate=26 February 2016}}</ref> The platform helps in the accommodation search for international students needing to secure a base for their studies from a distance.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://t3n.de/news/studentenbuden-ausland-startup-news-679107/ | title=Die besten Studentenbuden im Ausland: 60 Millionen Dollar für Student.com | accessdate=26 February 2016}}</ref> The website assigns the user to a personal booking consultant, who contacts the student to verify their details and needs, including choice of room, roommate, tenancy length, price and student status. The service is free for students and it takes its commission as a cut from bookings.<ref name="Bloomberg ">{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-02-11/website-that-helps-students-find-homes-abroad-gets-60-million | title=Website to Help Students Find Homes Gets $60 Million | publisher=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]] | accessdate=26 February 2016 | author=Jeremy Kahn}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pymnts.com/news/ecommerce/2016/student-com-secures-60m-from-spotify-and-its-backers/ | title=Student.com Secures $60M From Spotify And Its Backers | publisher=Pymnts | accessdate=26 February 2016}}</ref> In April 2016, Forbes revealed that billionaire investor, [[Jim Breyer]] invested an undisclosed amount in Student.com.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/stevenbertoni/2016/04/13/student-com-scores-powerful-silicon-valley-connection-with-breyer-capital-investment/#3f08b69566b0 | title=Student.com Scores Powerful Silicon Valley Connection With Breyer Capital Investment | publisher=Forbes | date=13 April 2016 | accessdate=15 May 2016 | author=Steven Bertoni}}</ref>
